     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Commas are the most common punctuation on the ACT English Test, appearing in 15-20 questions per test. To master comma questions, you need to understand the 4 types of commas and when each one should be used.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (EXACTLY 4 H3 SECTIONS)
     Each H3 = Major Concept
     Use BULLET POINTS with indents, NOT paragraphs
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. The Four Types of Commas
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The ACT tests exactly 4 comma rules—master these and you''ll handle every comma question
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Each type has a specific purpose and can''t be substituted with another</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Understanding when to use each type is critical for avoiding comma errors</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Type 1: Comma + FANBOYS
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Use a comma and a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">FANBOYS</strong> word to join two independent clauses
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">FANBOYS</strong> = For, And, Nor, But, Or, Yet, So</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "My alarm clock did not go off this morning, so I arrived late at school"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both sides must be independent clauses (complete sentences)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Type 2: Dependent Clause Followed by Independent Clause
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When a dependent clause comes before an independent clause, use a comma to separate them
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "While electronic music has become very popular, many people still prefer classic rock"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The dependent clause starts with subordinating conjunctions like while, although, because, if</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is from Chapter 1''s Rule #4 for compound sentences</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Type 3: Unnecessary Information
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Commas separate <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">unnecessary information</strong> from the rest of the sentence
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Information is unnecessary if you can remove it without fundamentally changing the sentence''s meaning</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Unnecessary information can be as short as one word or as long as a lengthy phrase</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Mrs. Ellison, who is known for giving pop quizzes, is my least favorite teacher"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The basketball team, though, did not mount a comeback this week"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Type 4: Listing
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Use commas when listing more than two items or with multiple adjectives modifying the same noun
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example with list: "The group ordered coconut shrimp, hot wings, and onion rings"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example with adjectives: "The old, limping dog still managed to complete the 3-mile hike"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use commas between all items in a series, including before the final "and" or "or"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 1 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->
<!-- Database: position=1, lesson_id=[UUID], shown AFTER teaching concept -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Unnecessary Information Commas
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The most common comma type on the ACT separates unnecessary information
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Information is unnecessary if removing it doesn''t fundamentally change the sentence''s meaning</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Unnecessary information can appear before a comma, after a comma, or between two commas</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">After removing unnecessary information, what remains must still be a complete sentence</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
The "Crossing-Out" Trick
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">To test if information is unnecessary, cross it out and read what remains
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the sentence is still complete and makes sense, the information is unnecessary</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the sentence becomes incomplete or loses critical meaning, the information is necessary (no commas)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The wooden beam, set at an angle, created an optical illusion"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Cross out "set at an angle" → "The wooden beam created an optical illusion" (still complete!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Necessary vs. Unnecessary Information
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Determining if information is truly unnecessary requires careful reading
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Correct (necessary): "The dresses that need to be hemmed are hanging in the closet"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Without "that need to be hemmed," we don''t know which specific dresses</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Correct (unnecessary): "Judith, who went to fashion school, designs dresses for a living"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">We already know who designs dresses (Judith), so the fashion school detail is extra</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
The Names Rule
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The ACT loves testing comma usage with names—you''ll see at least one question on this
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the identifier is NOT specific to one person (friend, teacher, physicist), the name is necessary—no commas</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "My friend Kelly recently moved to London" (I have multiple friends, so Kelly is necessary)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the identifier IS specific to one person (best friend, youngest sister, CEO), the name is unnecessary—use commas</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "My best friend, Andrew, is a certified scuba diver" (I have only one best friend)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
"That" vs. "Which" Phrases
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Phrases starting with <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">that</strong> never get commas—phrases starting with <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">which</strong> always get commas
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"That" phrases are always necessary information</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The dogs that live down the street are always barking"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Which" phrases are always unnecessary information</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "My neighbor''s dogs, which are always barking, love to play fetch"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Exception: Prepositional phrases like "on which," "in which," or "of which" don''t use commas before them</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
"ing" and "ed" Phrases
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Participle phrases</strong> starting with "ing" or "ed" may or may not need commas
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">On the ACT, "ing" and "ed" phrases most commonly appear with commas as unnecessary information</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Excited for the car ride, Jane''s bulldog started to jump up and down"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Marcus applied for the internship, hoping that he would get the position"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the phrase helps specify which noun, it''s necessary (no commas)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The politician waving to the crowd is predicted to win the election"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Prepositional Phrases
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Prepositional phrases</strong> consist of a preposition and its object
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Common prepositions: in, of, to, for, with, on, at, from, by, about, as, into, like, through, after, over, between, during, before, among, around</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Prepositional phrases at the FRONT of a sentence are always followed by a comma</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "On my way to work, I listened to my new favorite podcast"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Prepositional phrases in the MIDDLE or END almost never have commas (99% of the time)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The clothing on the bed is for vacation"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">They contain essential information specifying which noun you''re talking about</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 2 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->
<!-- Database: position=2, lesson_id=[UUID], shown AFTER teaching concept -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Transitional Words Like "However"
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Transitional words</strong> (also called conjunctive adverbs) require specific punctuation
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Common transitional words: however, though, therefore, instead, likewise, nevertheless, regardless, moreover, subsequently, furthermore, in addition, as a result, of course, otherwise, for example</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These are NOT FANBOYS—they require different punctuation</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Three Ways to Punctuate Transitional Words
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Position 1:</strong> At the front of the sentence followed by a comma
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "However, the truth would not be revealed until next week"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "As a result, the student was sent to the principal''s office"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This treats the transitional word as unnecessary information you can cross out</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Position 2:</strong> Separated by commas in the middle of a sentence
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The truth, however, would not be revealed until next week"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The student, as a result, was sent to the principal''s office"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Again, treat as unnecessary information between two commas</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Position 3:</strong> Separated by a semicolon and comma when between two independent clauses
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "I expected to pay over $100 for my new hiking boots; however, I found a sale and got them for half price"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Structure: Independent clause + semicolon + transitional word + comma + Independent clause</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">CRITICAL: You need BOTH the semicolon (before) AND the comma (after) the transitional word</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 3 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->
<!-- Database: position=3, lesson_id=[UUID], shown AFTER teaching concept -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Spotting Unnecessary Information Comma Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Unnecessary information comma questions have two defining characteristics
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The words in all 4 answer choices are exactly the same</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The only difference is where commas are located</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When you see this pattern, immediately use the "crossing-out" trick</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
How to Approach These Questions
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Read the entire sentence carefully
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Pay attention to any commas NOT in the underlined portion</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These fixed commas are often important clues for finding the correct answer</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Look out for sentence structure rules from Chapter 1 that may also apply</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Use the crossing-out trick systematically
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Test each answer choice by crossing out what the comma(s) would separate</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The correct answer leaves a complete, grammatical sentence after crossing out</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
The Pauses and Commas Backup Trick
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Read the sentence out loud (or "out loud" in your head on test day)
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you need to take a short pause for a breath, you likely need a comma</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is a backup method—always verify with the crossing-out trick first</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Natural pauses often correspond to where unnecessary information appears</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

