<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use subject pronouns (I, we, he, she, they, who) when the pronoun does the action, and object pronouns (me, us, him, her, them, whom) when it receives the action. For pronouns in lists, ignore the other items and read the pronoun alone. Pronouns in prepositional phrases are always object case. For "who" vs. "whom," replace with "he/him"—if "he" works, use "who"; if "him" works, use "whom."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Possessive pronouns must match the word they''re replacing in number. Remember that group nouns (team, committee, class) are singular and take singular possessive pronouns like "its," not "their."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Pronouns must agree with their antecedent (the noun they''re replacing) in both plurality and gender. A singular antecedent needs a singular pronoun; a plural antecedent needs a plural pronoun. Watch out for singular words like "each," "every," and "a person" that require singular pronouns.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Ambiguous pronouns are always incorrect. If you can''t tell exactly who or what a pronoun refers to, it''s ambiguous. The correct answer will replace the ambiguous pronoun with a specific noun. Watch for pronouns like he, she, they, it, this, that, some, and one in answer choices—they''re often ambiguous and need to be replaced with specific nouns.
  </li>
</ul>

