<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>A misplaced modifier is a word, phrase, or clause that is improperly separated from the noun it modifies, leading to a sentence with an incorrect or unintended meaning. Use the "next-door neighbor" rule: modifiers must be right next to the nouns they describe.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For front-of-sentence modifiers separated by a comma, the first noun after the comma must be what the modifier describes. Ask yourself: "Who or what is being described by this modifier?" and make sure that noun comes first after the comma.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For middle or end-of-sentence modifiers with commas (often using "which" or "that"), the modifier must come directly after the noun it describes. Check what noun comes right before the modifier—that''s what it''s currently modifying—and make sure it''s the correct noun.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Modifiers without commas follow the same "next-door neighbor" rule. Watch for phrases starting with "that" or words ending in "-ing" and "-ed." These descriptive phrases must be right next to the nouns they modify, whether at the beginning, middle, or end of the sentence.
  </li>
</ul>

