('parallel-structure', 'english', 'Topic 1.7 - Parallel Structure', 'Topic 1.7 - Parallel Structure...', 'intermediate', 30, 7, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.7
Topic: Parallel Structure
Lesson Key: parallel-structure
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING (2 SENTENCES MAX)
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Parallel structure questions make up about 7-9% of the ACT English Test—roughly 5-7 questions per test! These questions test whether items in a list or comparison are written with the same grammatical form.
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (4 H3 SECTIONS)
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. What is Parallel Structure?
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Parallel structure</strong> is the repetition of a chosen grammatical form within a sentence as items are listed or compared
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The items in a list can be words, phrases, or clauses</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Whenever we see items in a list or a comparison between items, we must make sure they have parallel structure</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Items in any list must be written with the same grammatical form
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Items must be all nouns, all verbs, all adjectives, etc.</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When lists are written with proper parallel structure, the sentence flows more smoothly and sounds better</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Many students can "hear" which answer choice is correct without even realizing they''re being tested on parallel structure</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Examples of Parallel Structure Errors
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "To protect her fragile hands, Julia will not rake the leaves, wash the dishes, and has decided she will not take out the trash."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">List items: "rake the leaves" (verb phrase), "wash the dishes" (verb phrase), "has decided she will not take out the trash" (clause)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Not parallel! The third item is much longer and has a different structure</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Correct: "To protect her fragile hands, Julia will not rake the leaves, wash the dishes, or take out the trash."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">All three items are now verb phrases: "rake," "wash," "take out"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Parallel!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 1 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Parallel Structure with Lists
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">No matter how simple or complex the items in the list are, they must be parallel
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Lists can contain nouns, verb phrases, adjectives, or entire clauses</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">All items must match in grammatical form</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Lists of Nouns or Noun Phrases
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "Elon Musk is known for self-driving cars and pioneering the SpaceX program."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Self-driving cars" (noun phrase) vs. "pioneering the SpaceX program" (verb phrase)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Not parallel!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Correct: "Elon Musk is known for self-driving cars and the SpaceX program."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both are noun phrases: "self-driving cars" and "the SpaceX program"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Also correct: "Elon Musk is known for manufacturing self-driving cars and pioneering the SpaceX program."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both are verb phrases: "manufacturing" and "pioneering"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Lists of Verb Phrases
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "After calling in sick to school, Charlie hoped to get excused from class, receiving an extension on his homework assignment, and spend the afternoon watching movies at home."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"To get excused" (infinitive), "receiving" (gerund), "spend" (base verb)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Not parallel!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Correct: "After calling in sick to school, Charlie hoped to get excused from class, receive an extension on his homework assignment, and spend the afternoon watching movies at home."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">All three use the base verb form after "hoped to": "get," "receive," "spend"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Parallel!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Lists of 3+ vs. Lists of 2
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Lists of 3 or more items are easier to spot
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You will be able to more obviously "hear" which answer choice is correct or incorrect</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "She made her bed, cleaned the shelves, and swept the floor" (all past tense verbs)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Lists of 2 are more difficult to spot and can trick you
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">They can often sound good even if they''re not parallel</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Be extra aware of parallel structure anytime you see a list of 2 on the ACT</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "It''s harder to lift the couch by myself than lifting it with some friends."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">✓ Correct: "It''s harder to lift the couch by myself than to lift it with some friends." (both use "to lift")</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 2 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Special Cases: Correlative Conjunctions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">In addition to lists, there are certain special cases for parallel structure
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These are officially called <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">correlative conjunctions</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">They must have the same grammatical structure for both parts of the conjunction</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
The Four Main Correlative Conjunctions
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Neither ___ nor ___
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The news report is neither accurate nor fair."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both blanks must have the same form (both adjectives here)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Either ___ or ___
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "You can either call me or text me."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both blanks must match (both verb phrases here)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Not only ___ but also ___
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is the most commonly tested correlative conjunction on the ACT</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "My mother not only took away my keys but also locked them in the safe."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both blanks must match (both verb phrases here)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Both ___ and ___
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Both a scholar and an athlete, Sylvia got a scholarship to row crew in college."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both blanks must match (both noun phrases here)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
How to Check Parallel Structure with Correlative Conjunctions
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Identify what comes immediately after the first part of the conjunction
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">What type of word or phrase follows "not only," "either," "neither," or "both"?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Check what comes immediately after the second part
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">What type of word or phrase follows "but also," "or," "nor," or "and"?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Make sure both parts match in grammatical form
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the first part has a verb phrase, the second must have a verb phrase</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the first part has a noun, the second must have a noun</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 3 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Parallel Structure Patterns
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Watch for these common patterns on the ACT
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Lists connected by "and" or "or"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Comparisons using "than"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Correlative conjunctions (neither/nor, either/or, not only/but also, both/and)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Strategy for Parallel Structure Questions
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step 1: Identify that there''s a list or comparison
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Look for words like "and," "or," "than," or correlative conjunctions</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step 2: Find all the items in the list or comparison
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">How many items are there? What are they?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step 3: Check the grammatical form of each item
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Is the first item a noun? Verb? Adjective? Phrase? Clause?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Are all the other items the same type?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step 4: Choose the answer that makes all items match
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">All items must have the same grammatical structure</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Trust your ear—parallel structure usually "sounds right"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 4 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 3: HIDDEN SEPARATOR
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 4: KEY TAKEAWAYS
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Parallel structure is the repetition of a chosen grammatical form within a sentence as items are listed or compared. Items in a list must all be the same type—all nouns, all verbs, all adjectives, etc. When lists have proper parallel structure, sentences flow smoothly and sound better.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Lists of 3 or more items are easier to spot because you can clearly hear when one item doesn''t match the others. Lists of 2 are trickier and can sound correct even when they''re not parallel, so pay extra attention to comparisons using "than" and two-item lists connected by "and" or "or."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Correlative conjunctions (neither/nor, either/or, not only/but also, both/and) require parallel structure on both sides. Whatever grammatical form comes after the first part must match the grammatical form that comes after the second part. "Not only/but also" is the most commonly tested on the ACT.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>To check parallel structure, identify all items in the list or comparison, determine the grammatical form of each item, and make sure they all match. Trust your ear—parallel structure usually sounds right, and non-parallel structure often sounds awkward or choppy.
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- MASTERY QUIZ: Stored in database, NOT in HTML -->
<!-- Create separately using quiz creation script -->
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('misc-topics', 'english', 'Topic 1.8 - Miscellaneous Topics', 'Topic 1.8 - Miscellaneous Topics...', 'intermediate', 30, 8, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.8
Topic: Other Miscellaneous Topics
Lesson Key: miscellaneous
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Miscellaneous grammar questions make up about 8-10% of the ACT English Test—roughly 6-8 questions per test! This chapter covers commonly confused words, active vs. passive voice, and other important grammar rules that don''t fit into other categories.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Commonly Confused Words
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The ACT tests many commonly confused words
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The most common is "affect" vs. "effect"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you''re unsure, go with your gut—you''ll usually be correct</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Affect vs. Effect
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Affect</strong> = verb meaning to act on or produce a change in
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Sunshine and palm trees affect my mood positively."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Effect</strong> = noun meaning the result of a change
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Sunshine and palm trees have a positive effect on my mood."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Other Commonly Confused Words
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Accept (receive) vs. Except (exclude)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Advice (noun - recommendation) vs. Advise (verb - to recommend)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Lie (to lie down) vs. Lay (to place)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Lose (to misplace) vs. Loose (not tight)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Passed (moved beyond) vs. Past (gone by in time)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Principal (head of school) vs. Principle (a rule)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Their (possessive) vs. There (location) vs. They''re (they are)</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">To (toward) vs. Too (also) vs. Two (2)</li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 1 -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Than vs. Then
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Than</strong> is ONLY used for comparisons
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "I think that chocolate with almonds is much better than ice cream."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Then</strong> has multiple meanings
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Used when dealing with time: "First we eat, then we clean up."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Means "in addition to": "I need to call my mother, and then we can leave."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Used with if/then statements: "If it rains, then we''ll stay inside."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Quick rule: For a comparison, use "than." Otherwise, use "then."</li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 2 -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Have vs. Of
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Many people mistakenly use "could of" or "would of"
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is ALWAYS incorrect!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The correct forms are "could have" or "would have"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The words "could," "should," "would," and "might" should always be followed by "have," not "of"
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The reason for this mistake: The contraction "could''ve" (short for "could have") is pronounced like "could of"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "If we left the show earlier, we could of avoided the traffic."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">✓ Correct: "If we left the show earlier, we could have avoided the traffic."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 3 -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Countable vs. Non-countable Adjectives
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">countable noun</strong> is something you can count
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Examples: bottles of milk, hours, trophies, calories</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">non-countable noun</strong> is something that cannot be expressed in plural form
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Examples: time, air, milk, significance</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Which Adjectives to Use
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">For COUNTABLE nouns, use: number, many, fewer, few
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The number of ingredients" (you can count ingredients)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "How many trophies" (you can count trophies)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Fewer calories" (you can count calories)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "A few minutes" (you can count minutes)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">For NON-COUNTABLE nouns, use: amount, much, less, little
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The amount of time" (you can''t count time itself)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "How much significance" (you can''t count significance)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Less whole milk" (you can''t count milk itself, only containers)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "A little time" (you can''t count time itself)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 4 -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Active Voice vs. Passive Voice
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Active voice</strong> means the subject performs the verb''s action
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "I picked up the pencil." (I performed the action)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The police chief announced the list of suspects." (The police chief performed the action)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Passive voice</strong> means the subject is acted upon by the verb
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The pencil was picked up by me." (The pencil didn''t do the action)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "The list of suspects was announced by the police chief." (The list didn''t do the action)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">On the ACT, NEVER select an answer choice in passive voice
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Active voice is always better than passive voice</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Active voice is clearer, more direct, and stronger</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 5 -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
6. Prepositional Idioms
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Idioms</strong> are expressions stated in a certain way because it''s widely accepted practice
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Certain words must be paired with certain prepositions to be correct</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These questions don''t come up often on the ACT</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When prepositional idioms appear, rely on what sounds best
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "Bobby was afraid by the dark."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">✓ Correct: "Bobby was afraid of the dark."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Common prepositional idioms to know
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Afraid of (not afraid by)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Anxious about (not anxious of)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Different from (not different than)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Responsible for (not responsible of)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 6 -->

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>"Affect" is a verb (to produce a change), while "effect" is a noun (the result of a change). "Than" is only for comparisons, while "then" is for time sequences or if/then statements. Always use "could have" not "could of"—the same applies to should, would, and might.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For countable nouns (things you can count), use number, many, fewer, and few. For non-countable nouns (things you can''t count in plural form), use amount, much, less, and little. For example: "fewer calories" but "less milk."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Active voice (where the subject performs the action) is always better than passive voice (where the subject is acted upon) on the ACT. Choose "I picked up the pencil" over "The pencil was picked up by me."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Prepositional idioms pair specific words with specific prepositions (like "afraid of" not "afraid by"). These questions are rare—when they appear, trust what sounds right. Don''t try to memorize every idiom; focus on mastering other topics first.
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('grammar-review', 'english', 'Topic 1.9 - Grammar Review', 'Topic 1.9 - Grammar Review...', 'intermediate', 30, 9, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.9
Topic: Grammar Review
Lesson Key: grammar-review
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> This <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">comprehensive grammar review</strong> synthesizes all the major concepts tested on the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">ACT English Test</strong>. Now that you''ve studied individual topics, it''s essential to develop <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">integrated strategies</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">error recognition patterns</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">efficient test-taking approaches</strong>. The ACT doesn''t announce which grammar rule each question tests—you must quickly identify error types and apply the appropriate fix. This lesson provides a systematic framework for approaching any grammar question with confidence and speed. </p> <h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;"> 1. The Complete Grammar Error Checklist </h3> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> When you encounter an underlined portion, systematically check for the most common error types. This mental checklist helps you identify problems quickly without wasting time. </p> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> The "Big 7" Grammar Categories </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> These seven categories account for approximately 70-80% of all grammar questions on the ACT: </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">1. Punctuation (15-18 questions)</strong> Commas, semicolons, colons, dashes, apostrophes <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">2. Sentence Structure (15-18 questions)</strong> Fragments, run-ons, comma splices, subordination <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">3. Verbs (8-10 questions)</strong> Agreement, tense, form, voice <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">4. Pronouns (5-7 questions)</strong> </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Agreement, case, clarity, reference <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">5. Modifiers (4-6 questions)</strong> Misplaced, dangling, squinting modifiers <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">6. Parallel Structure (3-5 questions)</strong> Lists, conjunctions, comparisons <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">7. Word Choice &amp; Idioms (3-5 questions)</strong> Commonly confused words, prepositional idioms </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Quick Diagnostic Questions </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Ask yourself these questions in order when you see an underlined portion: </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">→ Is there punctuation?</strong> Check comma rules, <span class="glossary-term" style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline; text-decoration-style: dotted; cursor: help;" title="Punctuation (;) that joins two complete sentences">semicolon</span>/<span class="glossary-term" style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline; text-decoration-style: dotted; cursor: help;" title="Punctuation (:) that introduces a list or explanation">colon</span> usage <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">→ Is there a verb?</strong> Check subject-verb agreement, tense, form <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">→ Is there a pronoun?</strong> Check agreement, case, clear antecedent <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">→ Does the sentence begin with a phrase?</strong> Check for dangling modifiers </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">→ Is there a list or conjunction?</strong> Check parallel structure <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">→ Can the sentence stand alone?</strong> Check for fragments/run-ons </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Common Error Combinations </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> The ACT often tests multiple concepts in one question. Watch for these combinations: </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fffbeb;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Comma + Verb Agreement:</strong> Prepositional phrase between subject and verb, with comma placement <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Modifier + Pronoun:</strong> Dangling modifier where the pronoun reference is ambiguous <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Parallel + Verb Tense:</strong> List items with inconsistent verb forms </p> </div> <h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;"> 2. Systematic Error Recognition Strategies </h3> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Develop a consistent approach to every grammar question. This systematic method prevents you from missing errors and helps you work efficiently under time pressure. </p> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Step 1: Read the Sentence Completely </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Always read from the beginning of the sentence (or previous sentence if needed) through the end. Context matters—you can''t identify tense errors, pronoun agreement, or modifier placement without understanding the full sentence. </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Why this matters:</strong> Many errors depend on elements outside the underlined portion. Subject-verb agreement requires finding the subject (often not underlined). Verb tense requires checking surrounding verbs. Pronoun clarity requires seeing the antecedent. </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Step 2: Trust Your Ear, But Verify with Rules </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> If something sounds wrong, it probably is. However, some errors sound correct (like "everyone...their"), so verify with the rules you''ve learned. </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ear + Rules = Accuracy</strong> → If it sounds wrong: Identify which rule is violated → If it sounds right: Still check the Big 7 categories systematically </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Step 3: Eliminate Obviously Wrong Answers </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Use process of elimination to narrow choices before identifying the specific error. </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Common eliminators:</strong> </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> • Creates a fragment or run-on • Uses wrong verb tense for the context • Creates pronoun agreement error • Breaks parallel structure in a list • Makes the sentence significantly more wordy without adding clarity </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Step 4: Look for Visual Cues </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Certain patterns in the answer choices tell you what the question is testing. </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fffbeb;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Different punctuation marks?</strong> → Punctuation question <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Different verb forms?</strong> → Verb agreement or tense <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Different pronouns?</strong> → Pronoun agreement or case <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Sentence restructured?</strong> → Modifier placement or sentence structure <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Different word order in list?</strong> → Parallel structure </p> </div> <h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;"> 3. Time Management and Pacing </h3> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> The ACT English section gives you 45 minutes for 75 questions across 5 passages. That''s 36 seconds per question or 9 minutes per passage. Effective time management is crucial for finishing strong. </p> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> The 9-Minute Per Passage Strategy </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Aim to complete each passage in approximately 9 minutes, which includes reading and answering all 15 questions. </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Minute 0-2:</strong> Read the passage naturally, answering inline grammar questions as you encounter them <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Minute 2-7:</strong> Work through remaining grammar and style questions systematically <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Minute 7-9:</strong> Handle rhetorical skills questions (organization, purpose, style) </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Quick vs. Slow Questions </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Not all questions take equal time. Recognize which should be fast and which require more thought. </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Quick questions (15-20 seconds):</strong> </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> • Obvious verb agreement errors • Clear punctuation rules (commas with introductory phrases) • Obvious fragments or run-ons • Word choice errors (their/there/they''re) </p> </div> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fffbeb;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Slower questions (45-60 seconds):</strong> </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> • Rhetorical skills (transitions, adding/deleting sentences) • Complex modifier questions requiring sentence restructuring • Pronoun clarity when multiple antecedents possible • Organization questions (sentence placement) </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> When to Skip and Return </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> If you''re stuck after 45 seconds, mark your best guess, circle the question number, and move on. Return to it if you have time at the end. </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Critical Strategy:</strong> Never leave questions blank. Even if you''re unsure, <span class="glossary-term" style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline; text-decoration-style: dotted; cursor: help;" title="Cross out wrong answer choices">eliminate</span> obviously wrong answers and make an educated guess. There''s no guessing penalty on the ACT. </p> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Pacing Checkpoints </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Check your progress at these intervals to ensure you''re on track: </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f8fafc;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">15 minutes:</strong> Should be finishing passage 2 (question 30) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">30 minutes:</strong> Should be finishing passage 4 (question 60) <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">40 minutes:</strong> Should be on passage 5 with 5 minutes to finish </p> </div> <h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;"> 4. Test Day Strategies and Final Tips </h3> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Beyond knowing grammar rules, test day success requires strategic approaches to maximize your score. These final strategies help you navigate the test efficiently and avoid common pitfalls. </p> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> When "NO CHANGE" Is Correct </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> About 20-25% of questions have "NO CHANGE" as the correct answer. Don''t avoid this choice if you can''t find an error. </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Choose NO CHANGE when:</strong> </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> • You''ve checked all grammar rules and found no violations • Other answer choices create new errors • Other choices are unnecessarily wordy • The original is clear, concise, and correct </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Shorter Is Usually Better </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> When choosing between grammatically correct options, the ACT typically favors conciseness. If two answers are both correct, choose the shorter one. </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Example:</strong> </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <span style="color: #dc2626;">✗ Wordy:</span> due to the fact that <span style="color: #16a34a;">✓ Concise:</span> because </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">However:</strong> Never sacrifice clarity or correctness for brevity. If the shorter version creates an error or changes meaning, choose the longer correct option. </p> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Avoid Extreme or Absolute Language </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> On rhetorical questions about adding/deleting information or main ideas, be wary of answer choices with extreme words like "always," "never," "only," "completely." </p> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Read Answer Choices Carefully </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> The ACT loves to include answer choices that look similar but differ in one key detail. Read every word of each choice. </p> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Common trap:</strong> Three choices are identical except one uses "affects" and another uses "effects." Missing this difference means picking the wrong answer. </p> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Grammar Doesn''t Always "Sound" Wrong </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Some grammatically incorrect constructions sound natural in casual speech. Trust the rules over your ear in these cases: </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #fffbeb;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> • "Everyone brought their book" sounds fine but is grammatically wrong (everyone = singular) • "Between you and I" sounds formal but is wrong (object of preposition = me) • "The team are winning" sounds right to some but is wrong (team = singular) </p> </div> <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 400;"> Final Mental Checklist </h4> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> Before moving to the next question, quickly verify: </p> <div style="border-left: 4px solid #16a34a; padding: 1rem; margin: 1rem 0; background-color: #f0fdf4;"> <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;"> <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Your answer creates no new errors <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> The sentence is complete and logical <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> All subjects have verbs and all verbs have subjects <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Pronouns have clear antecedents <span style="color: #16a34a; font-weight: 600;">✓</span> Modifiers are placed next to what they describe </p> </div> <p style="height: 1px; margin: 0; padding: 0;"></p><h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700; visibility: hidden; height: 0; margin: 0; padding: 0; overflow: hidden;">.</h3><h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;"> Key Takeaways </h3> <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;"> <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;"><span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>The Big 7 categories: Systematically check punctuation, sentence structure, verbs, pronouns, modifiers, parallel structure, and word choice for every underlined portion; these account for 70-80% of all grammar questions</li> <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;"><span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Systematic approach: Always read the complete sentence for context, trust your ear but verify with rules, <span class="glossary-term" style="color: #2563eb; text-decoration: underline; text-decoration-style: dotted; cursor: help;" title="Cross out wrong answer choices">eliminate</span> obviously wrong answers, and look for visual cues in answer choices to identify what''s being tested</li> <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;"><span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Time management: Aim for 9 minutes per passage (36 seconds per question); recognize quick questions (15-20 seconds) vs. slow questions (45-60 seconds); check pacing at 15, 30, and 40 minute marks</li> <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;"><span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Test day strategies: "NO CHANGE" is correct 20-25% of the time; when both answers are grammatically correct, choose the shorter one; never leave blanks (no guessing penalty); read all answer choices carefully</li> <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;"><span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Final verification: Before moving on, confirm your answer creates no new errors, the sentence is complete and logical, all subjects have verbs, pronouns have clear antecedents, and modifiers are correctly placed</li> </ul>')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('redundancy', 'english', 'Topic 2.1 - Redundancy & Wordiness', 'Topic 2.1 - Redundancy & Wordiness...', 'intermediate', 30, 10, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.10
Topic: Redundancy, Wordiness, and Irrelevance
Lesson Key: redundancy
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Redundancy, wordiness, and irrelevance questions appear frequently on the ACT English Test. For these questions, the shortest and simplest answer choice that expresses the same idea is almost always correct—if anything is redundant, wordy, or irrelevant, eliminate it.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Redundancy
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Redundancy</strong> occurs when information is unnecessarily repeated
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Read the sentence itself AND the sentence(s) before to check for repeated information</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If two words or phrases mean the same thing, one must be removed</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Common redundant phrases to watch for
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ "Returned back" → ✓ "Returned" (returning already means coming back)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ "In the Swedish forests" when Sweden was already mentioned → ✓ "In the forests"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ "Past history" → ✓ "History" (history is always past)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ "Free gift" → ✓ "Gift" (gifts are free by definition)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Example: Context-Based Redundancy
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "In Sweden, there are about 300,000 to 400,000 moose, many of which stand over seven feet tall, roaming freely in the Swedish forests."</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Correct: "In Sweden, there are about 300,000 to 400,000 moose, many of which stand over 7 feet tall, roaming freely in the forests."</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Why: The sentence already specifies the moose are in Sweden, so "Swedish" is redundant</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Wordiness
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Sentences can be unnecessarily wordy without being redundant
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Pick the answer choice that uses the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">fewest words</strong> to express the same idea</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Eliminate flowery or unnecessarily complex language</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Common wordy phrases and their concise alternatives
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ "Due to the fact that" → ✓ "Because"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ "At this point in time" → ✓ "Now"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ "In the event that" → ✓ "If"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">❌ "A cultural institution supporting intellectual endeavors related to renaissance art" → ✓ "A museum devoted to renaissance art"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Example: Simplifying Wordy Phrases
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "The ancient Italian sculptures were donated to a cultural institution supporting intellectual endeavors related to renaissance art."</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Correct: "The ancient Italian sculptures were donated to a museum devoted to renaissance art."</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Why: The simpler version conveys the exact same meaning with far fewer words</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Irrelevance
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Irrelevant information</strong> doesn''t contribute to the passage''s main idea or current paragraph
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Irrelevant details most often appear as long, wordy answer choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These answer choices are always incorrect</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Ask: Does this information help tell the story or explain the concept?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Example: Removing Irrelevant Details
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">❌ Incorrect: "To win the game, Ricky needed to make both free throws. Players are not allowed to step in the lane during a free throw attempt. He made the first one. The entire gym was quiet as he stepped to the line for the second."</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Correct: "To win the game, Ricky needed to make both free throws. He made the first one. The entire gym was quiet as he stepped to the line for the second."</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Why: The rule about stepping in the lane is irrelevant to Ricky''s specific free throw situation</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. How to Spot These Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The ACT directly tells you when testing redundancy, wordiness, or irrelevance
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Look for questions asking: "Which choice is the least redundant in context?"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Or: "Which choice best avoids wordiness and redundancy in context?"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When you see these questions, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">the shortest answer is almost always correct</strong></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Important warning: ONLY use "shortest is correct" for these specific questions
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">On grammar questions (not asking about redundancy), the shortest answer may be wrong</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: An ambiguous pronoun like "it" or "them" might be shortest but incorrect</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Always apply grammar rules first unless the question specifically asks about redundancy</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Recognizing Ambiguous Pronouns
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Even though pronouns are short, they''re incorrect if ambiguous
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Watch for: they, them, it, this, that, these, those, some, none</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you can''t tell exactly what the pronoun refers to, it''s incorrect</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "Freddie ordered some" is ambiguous—some what? Coral? Aquariums?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Correct: "Freddie ordered some coral colonies" clearly specifies what he ordered</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Redundancy occurs when information is unnecessarily repeated—check the current sentence and previous sentences for duplicate information. Common examples: "returned back" (just "returned"), "Swedish forests" when Sweden was already mentioned (just "the forests").
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Wordiness means using more words than necessary to express an idea. Pick the answer choice with the fewest words that conveys the same meaning: "because" instead of "due to the fact that," "museum" instead of "cultural institution supporting intellectual endeavors."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Irrelevant information doesn''t contribute to the passage''s main idea or current paragraph—these details often appear as long, wordy answer choices and are always incorrect. Ask yourself: does this information help tell the story or explain the concept?
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>The ACT directly asks "Which choice is the least redundant in context?" or "Which choice best avoids wordiness?" For THESE questions only, the shortest answer is almost always correct. However, on grammar questions, don''t always pick the shortest—ambiguous pronouns (it, them, some) may be short but incorrect.
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('word-choice', 'english', 'Topic 2.2 - Word Choice', 'Topic 2.2 - Word Choice...', 'intermediate', 30, 11, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.11
Topic: Word Choice
Lesson Key: word-choice
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Word choice questions appear on the ACT English Test and ask you to select the word that is clearest and most precise in context. These questions test your ability to read for context and choose the word that best conveys the intended meaning of the sentence.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Identifying Word Choice Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Word choice questions always have <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">4 words with no punctuation</strong> or the same punctuation
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The question asks: "Which choice is clearest and most precise in context?"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">All choices are grammatically correct</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You must select the word that best fits the meaning and tone</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">These questions test both vocabulary and context
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Some test word definitions (knowing what words mean)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Others test which word makes the most sense in this specific sentence</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Context is always the key to finding the right answer</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. How to Approach Word Choice Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Follow this three-step process
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Step 1:</strong> Read the sentence and surrounding sentences for context</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Step 2:</strong> Plug each word into the sentence one at a time</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Step 3:</strong> Pick the word that makes the most sense in context</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Context includes both meaning and tone
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Does the word''s definition fit logically?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Does the word''s formality level match the passage?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Does it create the intended relationship between ideas?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Example Approach
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Question: "Adding solar panels to your house can <u>emit</u> huge savings on energy bills."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A. emit</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">B. claim</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">C. gift</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">D. result in</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Analysis
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Emit" means to send out or release—doesn''t fit with savings</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Claim" means to assert or demand—doesn''t make sense here</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Gift" is a noun, not a verb that fits this context</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Result in" means to cause or produce—this fits perfectly!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The answer is D because "result in" is the only phrase that logically completes the meaning</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Vocabulary Strategy
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Don''t assume the hardest word is correct
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sometimes the ACT includes challenging vocabulary you need to know</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Other times, challenging words are incorrect answer choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The difficulty level of the word doesn''t indicate if it''s right or wrong</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">What to do when you don''t know a word
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you know a word works, pick it—even if it seems easy</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Eliminate words you know are wrong</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you don''t know a word and have to guess, make your best guess and move on</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t spend too much time on vocabulary you don''t know</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Trust What You Know
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Your instinct about common words is usually correct
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If a simple word like "make" or "show" fits perfectly, it''s likely correct</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t overthink or assume you need a fancier word</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The ACT values precision and clarity, not complexity</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Word Choice Patterns
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Similar-sounding words with different meanings
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Affect (verb - to influence) vs. Effect (noun - result)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Elicit (to draw out) vs. Illicit (illegal)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Complement (to complete) vs. Compliment (to praise)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Words with similar meanings but different connotations
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Dispassionate (unemotional) vs. Disinterested (unbiased) vs. Unbiased (neutral)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Display (to show) vs. Reveal (to uncover) vs. Exhibit (to demonstrate)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Context determines which shade of meaning is correct</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Phrasal verbs and preposition choices
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Improved over" vs. "improved upon" vs. "improved above"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The correct preposition changes the meaning</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Trust what sounds natural in standard English</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Word choice questions ask "Which choice is clearest and most precise in context?" and provide 4 words with the same punctuation. All choices are grammatically correct, so you must select based on meaning and context, not grammar rules.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use the three-step approach: (1) Read the sentence and surrounding context, (2) Plug each word into the sentence, (3) Pick the word that makes the most sense. Consider both the word''s definition and whether its formality level matches the passage.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Don''t assume the hardest vocabulary word is correct—sometimes challenging words are wrong answers. If you know a simple word works, pick it even if it seems easy. The ACT values precision and clarity over complexity.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Watch for similar-sounding words with different meanings (affect/effect, elicit/illicit), words with similar meanings but different connotations (dispassionate/disinterested), and phrasal verbs where the preposition matters ("improved over" vs. "improved above").
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('transitions', 'english', 'Topic 2.3 - Transitions', 'Topic 2.3 - Transitions...', 'intermediate', 30, 12, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.12
Topic: Transitions
Lesson Key: transitions
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Transition questions test your reading comprehension by asking you to select the word or phrase that best connects ideas between sentences. All answer choices will be grammatically correct, so you must read for context to determine which transition logically relates the ideas.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. How to Approach Transition Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Follow this three-step process
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Step 1:</strong> Ignore the transition currently in the passage—cover it up</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Step 2:</strong> Read the sentence(s) before and after to determine their relationship</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Step 3:</strong> Select the transition that correctly relates the ideas</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Context is everything
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You cannot determine the correct transition by reading only one sentence</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Always read both the previous and following sentences</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Ask: What is the relationship between these ideas?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Type 1: All Four Choices Are Transitions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When all 4 answer choices are transitions, you''re only being tested on selecting the correct one
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Read for context to understand the relationship</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Match the transition to the logical connection between ideas</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Example
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">"From a distance, the ocean looked pretty calm today even though a storm had arrived last night. <u>Under the circumstances,</u> the scene was much more chaotic with big waves and strong riptides."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A. NO CHANGE (Under the circumstances)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">B. For instance</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">C. Up close</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">D. For example</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Correct: C. "Up close" creates a contrast with "from a distance" in the previous sentence</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Type 2: Three Transitions and One "No Transition" Option
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When one choice has <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">no transition</strong>, the ACT is asking whether a transition is even necessary
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Most often, the correct answer is the one that removes the transition entirely</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Only use a transition if it properly links the sentences</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the ideas flow naturally without a transition, choose the "no transition" option</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
When to Remove Transitions
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Remove the transition if:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The sentences are simply continuing the same idea</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The relationship is already clear without a transition word</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Adding a transition makes the connection awkward or incorrect</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Transition Categories
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Contrast/Opposition:</strong> However, Nevertheless, On the other hand, In contrast, Despite this</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Example/Illustration:</strong> For example, For instance, Specifically, In particular</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Cause/Effect:</strong> Therefore, Consequently, As a result, Thus, Hence</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Addition:</strong> Furthermore, Moreover, Additionally, In addition, Also</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Time Sequence:</strong> Meanwhile, Subsequently, Previously, Ultimately, Finally</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Emphasis:</strong> Indeed, In fact, Certainly, Undoubtedly</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use the three-step approach: (1) Ignore the current transition, (2) Read sentences before and after to determine their relationship, (3) Select the transition that correctly connects the ideas. You cannot determine the correct transition by reading only one sentence.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>When all 4 choices are transitions, you''re choosing which relationship is correct (contrast, example, cause/effect, addition, etc.). When 3 choices are transitions and 1 has no transition, consider whether a transition is even necessary—most often, the correct answer removes the transition entirely.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Remove transitions when sentences simply continue the same idea, the relationship is already clear, or adding a transition makes the connection awkward. Only use a transition if it properly links the sentences and clarifies the relationship between ideas.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Know the main transition categories: Contrast (However, Nevertheless), Example (For instance, Specifically), Cause/Effect (Therefore, Consequently), Addition (Furthermore, Moreover), Time (Meanwhile, Subsequently), and Emphasis (Indeed, In fact).
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('which-choice', 'english', 'Topic 2.4 - Which Choice Questions', 'Topic 2.4 - Which Choice Questions...', 'intermediate', 30, 13, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.13
Topic: Which Choice Questions
Lesson Key: which-choice
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
"Which choice" questions ask you to make specific changes to a sentence, and the question itself tells you exactly what to do. These questions are easy to spot—they always include the words "which choice" or "which one" in the question.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. How to Identify and Approach These Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Easy to spot: Look for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">"which choice"</strong> or "which one" in the question
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The question tells you exactly what change to make</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">All answer choices are usually grammatically correct</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Your job: Figure out what the question asks and do exactly that
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t worry about grammar, conciseness, or style unless the question specifically asks</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Shorter is NOT always better on these questions</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Just answer the question—don''t overthink it!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Type 1: Specific Detail Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">These ask you to provide or emphasize a <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">specific detail</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Common phrasing: "most specifically describes," "most clearly emphasizes," "provides the most relevant detail"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Focus on the sentence you''re editing</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Read sentences before and after for context, but don''t rely on them too heavily</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Example: Specific Description
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Question: "Which choice most specifically describes what was used to build iceboxes?"</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Context: "Americans kept their food cold in iceboxes, <u>which required ice to be bought and placed into the box each week</u>."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A. NO CHANGE</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">B. which were only cold enough to keep food cool but not freeze anything</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">C. wooden boxes with tin and insulated with cork and sawdust</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">D. the very first invention that allowed people to keep food cold</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Answer: C—it''s the only choice that describes the materials used to build iceboxes</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Type 2: Emphasis and Tone Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">These ask you to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">emphasize a particular aspect</strong> or create a certain tone
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Common phrasing: "most clearly emphasizes," "best conveys," "creates the most vivid image"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Focus on which word choice highlights the specific quality mentioned</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Example: Emphasis
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Question: "Which choice most clearly emphasizes how the dinosaurs increase in size?"</li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Context: "Harold always begged for grow-in-water dinosaurs that <u>sprawl</u> when placed into water."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A. NO CHANGE (sprawl)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">B. change in size</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">C. expand</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">D. soak</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">✓ Answer: C—"expand" most clearly emphasizes the size increase</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Question Phrasings
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Questions asking for specific details
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Which choice most specifically describes..."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Which choice provides the most relevant detail about..."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Which choice best supports the claim that..."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Questions asking for emphasis or tone
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Which choice most clearly emphasizes..."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Which choice best conveys..."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Which choice creates the most vivid image of..."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The key strategy: Read the question carefully and give it exactly what it asks for—nothing more, nothing less</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>"Which choice" questions are easy to spot—they always include "which choice" or "which one" in the question. Your job is to figure out exactly what the question asks and select the answer that does that specific thing, not to fix grammar or improve style.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>All answer choices are usually grammatically correct, so don''t worry about grammar unless the question specifically asks about it. Shorter is NOT always better on these questions—choose the answer that best fulfills the specific request.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Specific detail questions ask for information about a particular aspect (materials, location, time, etc.). Choose the answer that provides that specific detail, even if other answers are more concise or sound better.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Emphasis and tone questions ask you to highlight a particular quality or create a certain feeling. Focus on which word choice best emphasizes the specific aspect mentioned in the question—don''t overthink it, just answer what''s asked!
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('adding-deleting', 'english', 'Topic 2.5 - Adding or Deleting Information', 'Topic 2.5 - Adding or Deleting Information...', 'intermediate', 30, 14, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.14
Topic: Adding or Deleting Information
Lesson Key: adding-deleting
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Adding or deleting information questions ask whether specific information should be included in a passage or not. For these questions, you must read for context—we recommend reading the entire paragraph where the question appears to determine if the information fits.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. How to Approach These Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Read the paragraph <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">twice</strong>: once with the information included and once with it deleted
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This makes it clear whether the information should be included</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Consider: Does the information fit the paragraph''s focus?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Depending on the question, you may need to read more than one paragraph</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Context is critical
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You must understand what the paragraph is discussing</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The information should support or relate to the main idea</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Adding Information Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">These questions give you a sentence or phrase and ask if it should be added
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Answer choices have two parts: (1) Yes or No, (2) Justification why</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">First decide yes or no, then pick the correct justification</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Critical Strategy: Only Consider What the Sentence Says
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When evaluating justifications, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">only consider the sentence being added</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Many students pick justifications that go far beyond what the sentence says</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t include details that have nothing to do with the sentence itself</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The justification must accurately describe what that specific sentence provides</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Example Structure
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Question: "Should the writer add this sentence about Dr. Anderson''s education?"
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A. Yes, because it establishes Dr. Paul''s mentor''s qualifications</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">B. Yes, because it indicates Dr. Anderson had a top-notch education</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">C. No, because it does not indicate where Dr. Paul studied</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">D. No, because it is not relevant to the passage''s discussion of Dr. Paul''s career</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">If the passage is about Dr. Paul''s career, not his mentor''s, the answer is D</li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Deleting Information Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">These ask if <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">existing information should be removed</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Same format: Yes/No + Justification</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Consider whether the information is relevant and necessary</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
When to Delete Information
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Delete when the information:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Is irrelevant to the paragraph''s main idea</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Repeats information already stated</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Distracts from the paragraph''s focus</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Doesn''t add anything meaningful</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Keep when the information:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Supports the main idea</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Provides necessary detail or clarification</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Connects ideas within the paragraph</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Answer Choice Patterns
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Good justifications are <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">specific and accurate</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">They describe exactly what the sentence provides</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">They relate to the paragraph''s focus</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "provides specific detail about the location" (if the sentence actually does that)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Bad justifications are vague or go too far
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">They claim the sentence says more than it actually does</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">They focus on irrelevant details</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "proves the scientist was the best in his field" (when sentence only mentions one achievement)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Common Wrong Answer Traps
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Watch out for justifications that:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Reference information NOT in the sentence being added/deleted</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Make logical leaps beyond what the sentence states</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Focus on the wrong person, topic, or idea</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use absolute language ("proves," "always," "never") when the sentence is less definitive</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Read the paragraph twice—once with the information included and once with it deleted. This approach makes it clear whether the information fits the paragraph''s focus and supports the main idea. Context is critical, so understand what the paragraph is discussing before deciding.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Answer choices have two parts: (1) Yes or No, (2) Justification. First decide yes or no, then pick the correct justification. The justification must accurately describe what the specific sentence provides—don''t pick options that go beyond what the sentence actually says.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Delete information when it''s irrelevant to the main idea, repeats what''s already stated, or distracts from the paragraph''s focus. Keep information when it supports the main idea, provides necessary detail, or connects ideas within the paragraph.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Avoid justifications that reference information NOT in the sentence, make logical leaps, focus on the wrong topic, or use absolute language when the sentence is less definitive. Good justifications are specific, accurate, and describe exactly what the sentence provides.
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('logical-placement', 'english', 'Topic 2.6 - Logical Placement', 'Topic 2.6 - Logical Placement...', 'intermediate', 30, 15, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v4.0
Subject: English
Topic Number: 1.15
Topic: Logical Placement
Lesson Key: logical-placement
-->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Logical placement questions ask you to place a sentence in the paragraph based on context and logical flow. These questions test your ability to recognize where information fits best by reading the sentences before and after each potential placement spot.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. How to Identify These Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Logical placement questions are easy to spot because they always ask <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">where to place a sentence</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Common phrasing: "For the sake of logic and coherence, Sentence X should be placed..."</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Or: "The sentence would most logically be placed..."</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Look for <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">bracketed numbers [1] [2] [3]</strong> at the beginning of sentences
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Bracketed numbers only appear when there''s a logical placement question</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Read these paragraphs more carefully—they may currently be out of order</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The paragraph may seem confusing at first because sentences are misplaced</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Bracketed letters [A] [B] [C] appear for end-of-passage placement questions
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t worry about the letters while reading—just note there will be a placement question</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The question will ask where to place a new sentence in the passage</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. The Critical Strategy: Plug and Read
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">To find the correct answer, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">plug the sentence into each potential spot</strong> and re-read
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t just read the sentence before the placement—this is the most common mistake</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You MUST read the sentence(s) before AND after where you''re placing it</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The correct placement should flow smoothly in both directions</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Step-by-Step Approach
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step 1: Read the entire paragraph first to understand the overall context
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Even if it seems confusing, get a sense of the topic and flow</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Identify what the paragraph is discussing</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step 2: Identify the sentence you need to place
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">What specific information does it contain?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">What does it refer to or connect to?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step 3: Test each answer choice by plugging in the sentence
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Read from the sentence before → through the placed sentence → to the sentence after</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Does it create smooth, logical flow?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Do pronouns have clear references?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Does the information follow a logical sequence?</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. What Makes a Placement Correct
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The correct placement creates <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">logical flow and coherence</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Information should follow a natural, chronological, or logical order</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Pronouns should refer to clearly established nouns</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Transition words should make sense in context</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Look for These Clues
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Pronouns and references
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the sentence says "This ultimately resulted in..." it must come after what caused the result</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If it says "he" or "she," the person must be introduced before</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Words like "this," "that," "these," "those" refer back to previously mentioned concepts</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Chronological order
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Events should follow time order unless context suggests otherwise</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Time markers like "first," "then," "after," "before" help establish sequence</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Topic continuity
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sentences discussing the same subtopic should be grouped together</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t interrupt one idea with an unrelated sentence</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Transition words and phrases
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"However," "in contrast," "on the other hand" signal a shift or contrast</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"For example," "such as" provide examples of previous statements</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"Further," "additionally," "moreover" add to previous points</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Mistakes to Avoid
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Not reading the sentence AFTER the placement
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is the #1 mistake students make</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You must check that the sentence flows into what comes next</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A sentence might connect well to what comes before but not to what comes after</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Not reading the entire paragraph first
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You need context to understand where the sentence fits</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Without reading the whole paragraph, you might miss important clues</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Choosing based on topic similarity alone
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Just because two sentences discuss the same topic doesn''t mean they belong together</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Check for logical sequence and smooth transitions</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Rushing through the answer choices
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Take time to actually plug in the sentence at each spot</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Read the surrounding sentences carefully for each option</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Logical placement questions ask "where should this sentence be placed?" Look for bracketed numbers [1] [2] [3] at the beginning of sentences—these only appear when there''s a logical placement question. Read these paragraphs carefully as they may currently be out of order.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>The critical strategy: plug the sentence into each potential spot and re-read the sentences before AND after. Many students only read before the placement—this is the #1 mistake! The correct placement must flow smoothly in both directions.
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Look for clues: pronouns and references (words like "this," "that," "he," "she" must refer to something previously mentioned), chronological order (events follow time sequence), topic continuity (related ideas stay together), and transition words ("however," "for example," "additionally").
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Read the entire paragraph first to understand context, then test each answer choice by actually plugging in the sentence at each spot. Don''t choose based on topic similarity alone—check for logical sequence, smooth transitions, and clear pronoun references.
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('2.2', 'math', 'Areas, Volumes & Triangles', 'Areas, Volumes & Triangles...', 'intermediate', 30, 7, '<!-- Topic 2.2: Areas, Volumes & Triangles -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.0 -->

<!-- 2-Sentence Intro (MAX 35-40 words, include ACT context) -->
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Geometry questions involving areas, volumes, and triangles appear on every ACT Math test, accounting for approximately 15-20% of all questions. Success on these problems requires memorizing key formulas and knowing when to apply specific triangle rules like <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Pythagorean theorem</strong> and special right triangle ratios.
</p>

<!-- H3 SECTION 1 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Area Formulas for Common Shapes
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">You MUST memorize these area formulas—they are NOT provided on the ACT:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Triangle</strong>: A = ½bh (where b = base, h = height)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Rectangle</strong>: A = lw (where l = length, w = width)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Square</strong>: A = s² (where s = side length)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Parallelogram</strong>: A = bh (base times height, NOT side lengths)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Trapezoid</strong>: A = ½(b₁ + b₂)h (average of the two bases times height)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Circle</strong>: A = πr² (where r = radius)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Kite</strong>: A = ½d₁d₂ (half the product of the diagonals)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Common mistakes to avoid:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For parallelograms, use the HEIGHT (perpendicular distance), not the slanted side length</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For circles, make sure you have the radius, not the diameter (if given diameter, divide by 2)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For triangles, the height must be perpendicular to the base</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Perimeter formulas you should know:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Rectangle</strong>: P = 2l + 2w</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Square</strong>: P = 4s</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Circle</strong> (circumference): C = 2πr or C = πd</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- H3 SECTION 2 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Volume Formulas and Unit Conversions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Essential volume formulas to memorize:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Rectangular Prism (box)</strong>: V = lwh</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Cube</strong>: V = s³</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Right Cylinder</strong>: V = πr²h</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Any 3D shape</strong>: V = Bh (where B = area of base, h = height)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Surface area formulas (less common but important):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Rectangular Prism</strong>: SA = 2lw + 2lh + 2wh</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Cube</strong>: SA = 6s²</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>CRITICAL: Unit conversions</strong>—The ACT frequently tests these, and students make costly mistakes:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Always convert units BEFORE calculating area or volume</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">1 yard = 3 feet</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">1 foot = 12 inches</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">1 square yard = 9 square feet (not 3!)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">1 square foot = 144 square inches (not 12!)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">1 cubic yard = 27 cubic feet (not 3!)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">1 cubic foot = 1,728 cubic inches (not 12!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Why you must convert FIRST:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: A field is 136 yards × 93 yards. To find area in square feet:</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">✓ CORRECT: Convert to feet first: (136 × 3) × (93 × 3) = 408 × 279 = 113,832 ft²</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">✗ WRONG: Calculate area then convert: 136 × 93 = 12,648, then × 9 = wrong answer!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- H3 SECTION 3 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Right Triangles and Pythagorean Theorem
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Pythagorean theorem</strong> applies ONLY to right triangles:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>a² + b² = c²</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Where a and b are the legs (the two shorter sides)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">c is the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">hypotenuse</strong> (the longest side, opposite the right angle)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Pythagorean triples</strong>—memorize these to save time:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>3-4-5 triangle</strong>: If you see sides of 3 and 4, the hypotenuse is 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>5-12-13 triangle</strong>: If you see sides of 5 and 12, the hypotenuse is 13</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These can be scaled up: 6-8-10, 9-12-15, 10-24-26, etc.</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you recognize a Pythagorean triple, you can skip the calculation entirely</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When to use Pythagorean theorem:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Finding the third side of a right triangle when you know two sides</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Finding distances in coordinate geometry problems</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solving problems with rectangles (diagonals create right triangles)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Working with circles and tangent lines</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- H3 SECTION 4 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Special Right Triangles (30-60-90 and 45-45-90)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>45-45-90 triangle</strong> (also called a right isosceles triangle):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Side ratio: <strong>x : x : x√2</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The two legs are equal (both length x)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The hypotenuse is x√2 (one leg times √2)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the leg is 5, the hypotenuse is 5√2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the hypotenuse is 10, each leg is 10/√2 = 5√2</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>30-60-90 triangle</strong>:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Side ratio: <strong>x : x√3 : 2x</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Short leg (opposite 30°): x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Long leg (opposite 60°): x√3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Hypotenuse (opposite 90°): 2x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>KEY RULE:</strong> The short leg is always half the hypotenuse</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the hypotenuse is 10, the short leg is 5, and the long leg is 5√3</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">How to recognize special right triangles:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Look for angle measurements (45°, 30°, 60°)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Look for the phrase "right isosceles triangle" (45-45-90)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Look for equilateral triangles split in half (creates 30-60-90)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you see √2 or √3 in the answer choices, it''s likely a special right triangle</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When to use special right triangles instead of Pythagorean theorem:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When you see the special angles (30°, 45°, 60°)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When the answer choices contain √2 or √3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Special triangles are FASTER than using a² + b² = c²</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- H3 SECTION 5 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Test-Taking Tips for Geometry Problems
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Draw and label diagrams</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If no diagram is provided, draw one yourself</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Label all given measurements directly on the diagram</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Mark right angles with a small square</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Write formulas next to the shapes as you work</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Look for Pythagorean triples first</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Before using a² + b² = c², check if the sides are a Pythagorean triple</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Common ones: 3-4-5, 5-12-13, 8-15-17, and their multiples</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This saves time and prevents calculation errors</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use substitution for complex problems</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If a problem uses variables (like "a field is l feet by w feet"), pick simple numbers</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: Let l = 4 and w = 3, then solve with those specific values</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This makes algebraic area/volume problems much easier to visualize</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Convert units before calculating</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">NEVER calculate area in yards and then convert to square feet</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ALWAYS convert the length and width first, then calculate</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Write out the conversion as a separate step to avoid mistakes</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Memorize formulas NOW, not the night before</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Make flashcards for all area and volume formulas</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Practice drawing and labeling 45-45-90 and 30-60-90 triangles from memory</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Review Pythagorean triples until you can recognize them instantly</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- HIDDEN SEPARATOR (required before Key Takeaways) -->
<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- KEY TAKEAWAYS (EXACTLY 4) -->
<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Memorize all area and volume formulas—they are NOT provided on the ACT, and you must know them cold to save time
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Always convert units BEFORE calculating area or volume (1 square yard = 9 square feet, NOT 3)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Recognize Pythagorean triples (3-4-5, 5-12-13) and special right triangles (45-45-90 ratio x:x:x√2, 30-60-90 ratio x:x√3:2x) to solve problems instantly
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For Pythagorean theorem, remember a² + b² = c² only works for right triangles, where c is always the hypotenuse (longest side)
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
