INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('2.3', 'math', 'Lines', 'Lines...', 'intermediate', 30, 8, '<!-- Topic 2.3: Lines -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.0 -->

<!-- 2-Sentence Intro (MAX 35-40 words, include ACT context) -->
<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Lines and linear functions appear frequently on the ACT Math test, testing your ability to calculate <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">slope</strong>, write equations, and use coordinate geometry formulas. Mastering the different forms of linear equations and understanding parallel/perpendicular relationships is essential for scoring well on these questions.
</p>

<!-- H3 SECTION 1 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Slope and Its Properties
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Slope</strong> formula for any two points (x₁, y₁) and (x₂, y₂):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Slope = (y₁ - y₂) / (x₁ - x₂) = rise / run</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Rise = change in y-coordinates</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Run = change in x-coordinates</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Understanding slope values:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Positive slope</strong>: Line goes up and to the right</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Negative slope</strong>: Line goes down and to the right</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Higher slope</strong>: Steeper line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Lower slope</strong>: Flatter line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Zero slope</strong>: Horizontal line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Undefined slope</strong>: Vertical line</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Parallel lines</strong>: Same slope
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If line A has slope 3, any line parallel to it also has slope 3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Parallel lines never intersect</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Perpendicular lines</strong>: Slopes are negative reciprocals
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">To find the negative reciprocal: flip the fraction and change the sign</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If line A has slope 2/3, a perpendicular line has slope -3/2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If line A has slope 4, a perpendicular line has slope -1/4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If line A has slope -5, a perpendicular line has slope 1/5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Perpendicular lines intersect at 90 degrees</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- H3 SECTION 2 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Slope-Intercept Form (y = mx + b)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The most common and useful form of a linear equation:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>y = mx + b</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">m = slope (steepness of the line)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">b = y-intercept (where the line crosses the y-axis)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Reading information from the equation:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: y = 3x - 5 has slope 3 and y-intercept -5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: y = -2x + 7 has slope -2 and y-intercept 7</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: y = (1/2)x + 4 has slope 1/2 and y-intercept 4</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Reading information from a graph:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Find the y-intercept: where the line crosses the y-axis</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Find the slope: pick two points and calculate rise/run</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Or count: "up 2, right 1" means slope = 2/1 = 2</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When to use slope-intercept form:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When you know the slope and y-intercept</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When you need to quickly identify slope or y-intercept from an equation</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When graphing a line</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- H3 SECTION 3 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Point-Slope Form and Standard Form
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Point-slope form</strong>: Use when you know a point and the slope
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>y - y₁ = m(x - x₁)</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">(x₁, y₁) is a point on the line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">m is the slope</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">After plugging in values, solve for y to convert to slope-intercept form</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Alternative method: Plug point into y = mx + b
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you know the slope m, write: y = mx + b</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Plug in the (x, y) values of a point on the line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solve for b to find the y-intercept</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This often feels more intuitive than point-slope form</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Standard form</strong>: Less common but sometimes useful
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Ax + By = C</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A, B, and C are constants (usually integers)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">To find slope from standard form: slope = -A/B</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">To find y-intercept: set x = 0 and solve for y</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">To find x-intercept: set y = 0 and solve for x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Usually easier to convert to slope-intercept form first</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- H3 SECTION 4 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Midpoint and Distance Formulas
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Midpoint formula</strong>: Finds the point exactly halfway between two points
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Midpoint = ((x₁ + x₂)/2, (y₁ + y₂)/2)</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Average the x-coordinates, average the y-coordinates</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: Midpoint of (2, 5) and (8, 13) = ((2+8)/2, (5+13)/2) = (5, 9)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Distance formula</strong>: Finds the straight-line distance between two points
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Distance = √[(x₁ - x₂)² + (y₁ - y₂)²]</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is the Pythagorean theorem applied to coordinates</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">(x₁ - x₂) is the horizontal distance</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">(y₁ - y₂) is the vertical distance</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Square both, add them, then take the square root</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Relationship between distance and Pythagorean theorem:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The distance formula IS the Pythagorean theorem</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The two points form a right triangle with legs (x₁ - x₂) and (y₁ - y₂)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The distance is the hypotenuse</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sometimes it''s easier to draw the triangle and use a² + b² = c²</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- H3 SECTION 5 -->
<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Test-Taking Tips for Line Questions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Always convert to y = mx + b when possible</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Slope-intercept form is the easiest to work with</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If given standard form, solve for y immediately</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If given point-slope form, distribute and solve for y</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>For perpendicular lines, flip and negate the slope</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Perpendicular slope = -1 / (original slope)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If slope is 2, perpendicular is -1/2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If slope is -3/4, perpendicular is 4/3</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use substitution to verify equations</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If given a point and asked which equation represents the line, plug the point into each answer choice</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The correct equation will make the point satisfy the equation</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This can be faster than calculating slope and y-intercept</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Draw quick sketches for visual problems</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If given two points, plot them quickly on scratch paper</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Visualize the slope (is it positive or negative? steep or flat?)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This helps catch sign errors and eliminate wrong answers</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Memorize the formulas</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Slope formula, midpoint formula, and distance formula must be memorized</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">They are NOT provided on the ACT</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Practice writing them from memory until automatic</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- HIDDEN SEPARATOR (required before Key Takeaways) -->
<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<!-- KEY TAKEAWAYS (EXACTLY 4) -->
<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Parallel lines have the same slope, perpendicular lines have negative reciprocal slopes (flip fraction and change sign)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Always convert equations to y = mx + b form when possible—it makes finding slope and y-intercept immediate
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Memorize: slope = (y₁-y₂)/(x₁-x₂), midpoint = ((x₁+x₂)/2, (y₁+y₂)/2), distance = √[(x₁-x₂)² + (y₁-y₂)²]
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>The distance formula is just the Pythagorean theorem applied to coordinates—sometimes it''s easier to draw the right triangle
  </li>
</ul>
