INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('2.4', 'math', 'Arcs and Sectors', 'Arcs and Sectors...', 'intermediate', 30, 9, '<!-- Topic 2.4: Arcs and Sectors -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.0 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Arcs and sectors appear occasionally on the ACT Math test, usually 1-2 questions per test. These problems test your understanding of how parts of a circle relate to the whole circle using proportional reasoning with central angles.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Understanding Arcs
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">An <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">arc</strong> is a portion of a circle''s circumference
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Think of it as a "slice" of the circle''s edge</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Arcs are measured in two ways: degree measure or arc length</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Degree measure of an arc:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Equal to the measure of the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">central angle</strong> that intercepts it</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A central angle is an angle whose vertex is at the center of the circle</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: If the central angle is 90°, the arc measures 90°</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Arc length (the actual distance along the curve):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Arc length is a portion of the total circumference</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use the proportion: arc length / circumference = angle / 360°</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Arc length formula (MEMORIZE THIS):</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Arc Length = (θ/360°) × 2πr</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Where θ = central angle in degrees</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">r = radius of the circle</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">2πr = circumference of the whole circle</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Alternative form (same formula):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Arc Length / Circumference = θ / 360°</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This proportion shows: arc is to whole circle as angle is to 360°</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Useful when you need to solve for the angle or radius</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Understanding Sectors
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">A <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">sector</strong> is a "slice" of a circle (like a pizza slice)
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Bounded by two radii and an arc</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sectors have area, just like the whole circle has area</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Sector area formula (MEMORIZE THIS):</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Sector Area = (θ/360°) × πr²</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Where θ = central angle in degrees</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">r = radius of the circle</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">πr² = area of the whole circle</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Alternative form (proportion):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Sector Area / Circle Area = θ / 360°</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This shows: sector is to whole circle as angle is to 360°</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Key pattern to recognize:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Arc length uses circumference (2πr)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sector area uses circle area (πr²)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both use the same proportion: (θ/360°)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Solving Arc and Sector Problems
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step-by-step approach for arc length:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Identify the central angle (θ) and radius (r)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Calculate the full circumference: 2πr</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Find the fraction: θ/360°</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 4: Multiply: arc length = (θ/360°) × 2πr</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step-by-step approach for sector area:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Identify the central angle (θ) and radius (r)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Calculate the full circle area: πr²</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Find the fraction: θ/360°</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 4: Multiply: sector area = (θ/360°) × πr²</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Working backwards (finding angle or radius):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If given arc length and radius, solve for θ</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If given sector area and angle, solve for r</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use algebra to isolate the unknown variable</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Common question types:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Given angle and radius, find arc length or sector area</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Given arc length and radius, find the central angle</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Given sector area and angle, find the radius</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Finding the difference between two arcs or sectors</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Test-Taking Tips for Arcs and Sectors
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Think in terms of proportions</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The key insight: the arc/sector is a fraction of the whole circle</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">That fraction equals the central angle divided by 360°</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: A 90° angle means 90/360 = 1/4 of the circle</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Don''t confuse arc length with sector area</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Arc length is distance (1-dimensional) - uses circumference</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sector area is space (2-dimensional) - uses circle area</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Read the question carefully to determine which one is asked</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Memorize the formulas now</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Arc length = (θ/360°) × 2πr</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sector area = (θ/360°) × πr²</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These are NOT provided on the test</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use the proportion setup for complex problems</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Arc/Circumference = Angle/360° is easier to manipulate algebraically</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Especially useful when solving for the angle or radius</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Cross-multiply to solve</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Simplify the fraction θ/360° early</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">90/360 = 1/4, 120/360 = 1/3, 180/360 = 1/2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This makes calculations much simpler</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (90/360) × 2π(12) = (1/4) × 24π = 6π</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Arc length = (θ/360°) × 2πr and Sector area = (θ/360°) × πr²—these formulas are NOT provided on the ACT
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>The central angle determines what fraction of the circle you have: a 90° angle = 1/4 of the circle
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Arc length is 1-dimensional (uses circumference 2πr), sector area is 2-dimensional (uses circle area πr²)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Think proportionally: arc/circumference = sector/circle = angle/360°—this relationship solves all arc and sector problems
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('3.4', 'math', 'Logarithms', 'Logarithms...', 'intermediate', 30, 10, '<!-- Topic 3.4: Logarithms -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.0 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Logarithms appear 1-2 times per ACT Math test, usually testing your ability to convert between <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">logarithmic form</strong> and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">exponential form</strong>. Understanding this conversion is the key to solving almost all logarithm questions on the ACT.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Basics of Logarithms (Converting Between Forms)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The fundamental relationship between logs and exponents:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>log_a(b) = c</strong> is the same as <strong>a^c = b</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Where a is the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">base</strong>, c is the exponent, and b is the result</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both equations describe the exact same relationship—just different notation</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Examples of converting from <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">logarithmic form</strong> to <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">exponential form</strong>:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">log₃(3) = 1 → 3¹ = 3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">log₃(9) = 2 → 3² = 9</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">log₃(27) = 3 → 3³ = 27</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The pattern: "log base 3 of 27 equals 3" means "3 to the 3rd power equals 27"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">How to solve logarithm equations:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Convert from logarithmic form to exponential form</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Solve the exponential equation using exponent rules</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: When log₄(x) = 3, what is x?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Convert: 4³ = x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solve: x = 64</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">CRITICAL strategy:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Almost ALL ACT logarithm questions are solved by converting to exponential form</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you can convert, you can solve the problem</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Practice this conversion until it''s automatic!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Using Your Calculator (Change of Base Rule)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">change of base rule</strong> lets you use a calculator:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>log_b(a) = log(a) / log(b)</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This converts ANY logarithm to base 10 (which calculators can compute)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: log₃(9) = log(9) / log(3) = 0.954 / 0.477 = 2</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Using the change of base rule on your calculator:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">To find log₃(9): Enter log(9) ÷ log(3) in calculator</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">To find log₂(8): Enter log(8) ÷ log(2) in calculator</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This works for ANY base and ANY value</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Some calculators have a built-in logbase function:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>TI-83/84:</strong> Press MATH, scroll to LOGBASE</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This allows direct entry: logbase(3, 9) = 2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Check if your calculator has this feature—it''s faster!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Calculator method vs. algebraic method:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For simple bases (2, 3, 4, 5): Converting to exponential form is often faster</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For complex problems with multiple logs: Use change of base rule</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 5(log₃(9) + log₂(8)) can be solved entirely with calculator</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Logarithm Rules (For Advanced Questions)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Four logarithm rules you should know:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Product Rule:</strong> log_a(xy) = log_a(x) + log_a(y)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Quotient Rule:</strong> log_a(x/y) = log_a(x) - log_a(y)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Power Rule:</strong> log_a(x^n) = n·log_a(x)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Log of 1:</strong> log_a(1) = 0 (because a⁰ = 1)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When to use these rules:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These appear RARELY on the ACT (1-2 times per test, if at all)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Most often on the LAST 10 questions (hardest section)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Students aiming for 30+ should memorize these</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Other students can skip—focus on conversion first!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example using power rule:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If log₉(3^x) = 3/2, what is x?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use power rule: x·log₉(3) = 3/2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Find log₉(3) using change of base: log(3)/log(9) = 1/2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Substitute: x·(1/2) = 3/2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solve: x = 3</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Shortcut - backsolving with calculator:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If answer choices are given, plug each one in</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use change of base rule to evaluate both sides</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The correct answer makes both sides equal</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is often faster than using logarithm rules!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Natural Logarithms (ln)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Natural logarithms</strong> use base e (approximately 2.71828):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>ln(b) = c</strong> is the same as <strong>e^c = b</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The base "e" is invisible—it''s always e for natural logs</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ln is just shorthand notation for log_e</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Natural logarithms appear VERY rarely:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Usually only in the last 5-10 questions (hardest section)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Students rushing through can skip this topic entirely</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Students aiming for 30+ should learn the basics</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Solving natural logarithm equations:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: If ln(x-1) = 3, then x = ?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Convert to exponential form: e³ = x-1</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Solve for x: x = e³ + 1</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Same conversion strategy as regular logarithms!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">All logarithm rules work for natural logs too:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ln(xy) = ln(x) + ln(y)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ln(x/y) = ln(x) - ln(y)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ln(x^n) = n·ln(x)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ln(1) = 0</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Test-Taking Tips for Logarithms
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Master the conversion between logarithmic and exponential form</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is THE most important skill for ACT logarithm questions</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Practice until you can convert instantly without thinking</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Almost every logarithm question becomes easy once you convert</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use your calculator with the change of base rule</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">log_b(a) = log(a) / log(b) works for ANY logarithm</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This lets you evaluate complex expressions quickly</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Check if your calculator has a built-in logbase function</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Backsolve when answer choices are given</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Plug each answer choice into the original equation</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use change of base rule to evaluate on calculator</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Often faster than using logarithm rules algebraically</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Prioritize logarithm rules based on your target score</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Target score below 28: Focus ONLY on conversion and change of base</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Target score 28-32: Memorize the four logarithm rules</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Target score 33+: Learn natural logarithms too</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t waste time on rare topics if you need basics first!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Remember: logarithms are just another form of exponents</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you understand exponents well, logarithms become easier</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The conversion is the bridge between the two</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">All logarithm rules mirror exponent rules</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Convert between forms: log_a(b) = c means a^c = b—this conversion solves almost all ACT logarithm questions
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use change of base rule with calculator: log_b(a) = log(a) / log(b) to evaluate any logarithm quickly
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Memorize logarithm rules (product, quotient, power, log of 1) only if aiming for 30+—they appear rarely
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Natural logarithms (ln) use base e and follow the same conversion strategy: ln(b) = c means e^c = b
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('2.5', 'math', 'Circles, Ellipses, and Hyperbolas', 'Circles, Ellipses, and Hyperbolas...', 'intermediate', 30, 10, '<!-- Topic 2.5: Circles, Ellipses, and Hyperbolas -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.0 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Conic sections (circles, ellipses, and hyperbolas) appear 1-3 times per ACT Math test, usually focusing on the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">equation of a circle</strong> in standard form. Understanding how to identify the center and radius from the equation is the most important skill for these questions.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Equation of a Circle
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Standard form</strong> of a circle (MEMORIZE THIS):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>(x - h)² + (y - k)² = r²</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Center: (h, k)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Radius: r</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Reading the center from the equation:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (x - 3)² + (y + 5)² = 16 has center (3, -5)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Watch the signs!</strong> (x - h) means center x = +h, (y + k) means center y = -k</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If (x - 3), the center x-coordinate is 3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If (y + 5), the center y-coordinate is -5 (opposite sign!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Finding the radius:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">r² is on the right side of the equation</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (x - 2)² + (y - 1)² = 25 has r² = 25, so r = 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (x + 1)² + (y - 3)² = 100 has r² = 100, so r = 10</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t forget to take the square root!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Special case - circle centered at origin:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>x² + y² = r²</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Center: (0, 0)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: x² + y² = 49 is centered at origin with radius 7</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Writing the equation when given center and radius:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Center (3, -2) and radius 5: (x - 3)² + (y + 2)² = 25</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Center (-4, 7) and radius 6: (x + 4)² + (y - 7)² = 36</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Remember to square the radius!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Completing the Square for Circles
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Sometimes circle equations are given in <strong>expanded form</strong>:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: x² + 4x + y² - 8y + 5 = 0</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This doesn''t look like standard form!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You must <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">complete the square</strong> to find center and radius</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Steps to complete the square:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Group x terms and y terms: (x² + 4x) + (y² - 8y) = -5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: For x terms, take half of coefficient of x, square it: (4/2)² = 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: For y terms, take half of coefficient of y, square it: (-8/2)² = 16</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 4: Add these to both sides: (x² + 4x + 4) + (y² - 8y + 16) = -5 + 4 + 16</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 5: Factor: (x + 2)² + (y - 4)² = 15</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Now you can read center (-2, 4) and radius √15</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Quick formula for completing the square:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For x² + bx, add (b/2)²</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This creates a perfect square: (x + b/2)²</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Same process for y terms</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Ellipses and Hyperbolas (Basic Recognition)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Ellipse</strong> standard form:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>(x - h)²/a² + (y - k)²/b² = 1</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Center: (h, k), just like a circle</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Looks like a stretched or compressed circle</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both terms are added (+), both squared</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (x - 2)²/9 + (y + 1)²/4 = 1 is centered at (2, -1)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Hyperbola</strong> standard form:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>(x - h)²/a² - (y - k)²/b² = 1</strong> or <strong>(y - k)²/b² - (x - h)²/a² = 1</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Center: (h, k)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Has two separate curved branches</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Key difference: One term is subtracted (-)</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (x - 3)²/16 - (y + 2)²/9 = 1 is centered at (3, -2)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">How to identify which conic section:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Circle</strong>: x² and y² have same coefficient, added together</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Ellipse</strong>: x² and y² have different coefficients, added together</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Hyperbola</strong>: x² and y² are subtracted</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">On the ACT:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Circles are tested most frequently</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Ellipses and hyperbolas appear 0-2 times per test</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Usually just need to identify center or general shape</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Deep knowledge of ellipse/hyperbola properties rarely needed</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Test-Taking Tips for Conic Sections
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Master the circle equation first</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">(x - h)² + (y - k)² = r² is the most tested formula</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Practice reading the center until automatic</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Remember: opposite signs! (x - 3) means center x = 3</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Watch for completing the square questions</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the equation isn''t in standard form, you''ll need to complete the square</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Take half the coefficient, square it, add to both sides</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t forget to move the constant to the other side first!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use the signs to identify the conic</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both terms positive (+)? Circle or ellipse</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">One term negative (-)? Hyperbola</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This quick check eliminates wrong answers fast</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Radius is always positive</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">r² = 25 means r = 5 (not ±5)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Radius cannot be negative in geometry</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Memorize the standard forms</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Circle: (x-h)²+(y-k)²=r²</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Ellipse: (x-h)²/a²+(y-k)²/b²=1</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Hyperbola: (x-h)²/a²-(y-k)²/b²=1</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These formulas are NOT provided on the test</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Circle equation (x-h)²+(y-k)²=r² with center (h,k) and radius r—watch the signs! (x-3) means center x=3, (y+5) means center y=-5
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>To complete the square for x²+bx, add (b/2)² to create a perfect square (x+b/2)²
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Identify conics by signs: both terms positive = circle/ellipse, one term negative = hyperbola
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Focus on circles first—they appear most frequently on the ACT, while ellipses and hyperbolas are rare
  </li>
</ul>
')
