INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('3.5', 'math', 'Inequalities', 'Inequalities...', 'intermediate', 30, 11, '<!-- Topic 3.5: Inequalities -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.0 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Inequalities appear 2-4 times per ACT Math test, testing your ability to solve algebraic inequalities and graph them on number lines or coordinate planes. The most important rule: flip the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">inequality sign</strong> when multiplying or dividing by a negative number.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Solving Algebraic Inequalities
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Treat inequality signs (<, >, ≤, ≥) like an equals sign:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use all normal algebra rules: add, subtract, combine like terms</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Isolate the variable just like solving equations</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The inequality sign stays the same for most operations</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>CRITICAL RULE: Flip the sign when multiplying or dividing by a negative</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is the #1 mistake students make with inequalities!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: -2x + 5 < 11</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Subtract 5: -2x < 6</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Divide by -2: x > -3 (sign flipped from < to >!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When NOT to flip the sign:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ONLY flip when you multiply or divide BOTH SIDES by a negative</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t flip just because you see a negative number somewhere!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 3x + 6 > x - 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Combine: 2x > -10</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Divide by 2 (positive): x > -5 (sign stays the same!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step-by-step process:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Move all variable terms to one side</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Move all number terms to the other side</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Combine like terms</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 4: Divide to isolate variable (flip sign if dividing by negative!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Graphing Inequalities on a Number Line
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Two types of circles on number lines:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Open circle (○):</strong> Use for > and < (strict inequalities)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The endpoint is NOT included in the solution</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: x > 3 has an open circle at 3</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Solid circle (●):</strong> Use for ≥ and ≤ (inclusive inequalities)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The endpoint IS included in the solution</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: x ≥ 3 has a solid circle at 3</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Which direction to shade:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Greater than (> or ≥):</strong> Shade to the RIGHT</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: x ≥ 10/3 → solid circle at 10/3, shade right</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Less than (< or ≤):</strong> Shade to the LEFT</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: x < -5 → open circle at -5, shade left</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Quick memory trick:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The inequality sign "points" to the smaller values</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">So x > 3 means x is to the RIGHT of 3 (bigger values)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">And x < 3 means x is to the LEFT of 3 (smaller values)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Graphing Linear Inequalities in the Coordinate Plane
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Three-step process for graphing linear inequalities:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Rearrange into y = mx + b form (slope-intercept)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Plot the line (dashed or solid based on inequality)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Shade the solution region (above or below the line)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Dashed vs. solid lines:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Dashed line:</strong> Use for > and < (strict inequalities)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Points ON the line are NOT part of the solution</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Solid line:</strong> Use for ≥ and ≤ (inclusive inequalities)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Points ON the line ARE part of the solution</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Where to shade:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Greater than (> or ≥):</strong> Shade ABOVE the line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: y ≥ 2x + 3 → solid line, shade above</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Less than (< or ≤):</strong> Shade BELOW the line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: y < -x + 2 → dashed line, shade below</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Graph 2x + 3y ≥ 6
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Solve for y: 3y ≥ -2x + 6 → y ≥ (-2/3)x + 2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Draw solid line (because of ≥)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Shade above the line (because of ≥)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Systems of Inequalities and Advanced Graphing
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Systems of inequalities (multiple inequalities on same graph):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Graph each inequality separately on the same coordinate plane</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The solution is where the shaded regions OVERLAP</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: y < 2x - 4 AND y > -(1/3)x - 2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Graph both lines, shade both regions, find the overlap</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Parabola inequalities (follow same rules as lines):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Greater than (> or ≥):</strong> Shade ABOVE the parabola</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Less than (< or ≤):</strong> Shade BELOW the parabola</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use dashed curve for > and <, solid curve for ≥ and ≤</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Circle and ellipse inequalities (different shading rules):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Greater than (> or ≥):</strong> Shade OUTSIDE the circle/ellipse</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (x-2)² + (y-1)² > 4 → shade outside the circle</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Less than (< or ≤):</strong> Shade INSIDE the circle/ellipse</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (x-2)²/4 + (y-1)²/9 ≤ 1 → shade inside the ellipse</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When you''ll see advanced inequalities:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Parabola/circle/ellipse inequalities appear in the LAST 10 questions</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">These are for students aiming for 30+ scores</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Master linear inequalities first before worrying about these!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Test-Taking Tips for Inequalities
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Write "FLIP SIGN" when dividing by negatives</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is the most common mistake on inequality questions</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Circle any negative you''re dividing by to remind yourself</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Double-check the final sign before selecting your answer</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use test points to check your graph shading</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Pick a point in the shaded region (like (0,0) if it''s not on the line)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Plug it into the original inequality</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If it makes the inequality true, you shaded correctly!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If false, you shaded the wrong side</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Remember: Open vs solid circles/lines</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">< and > → open circle/dashed line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">≤ and ≥ → solid circle/solid line</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ACT answer choices often differ only in this detail!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>For systems, look for the overlap</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The solution to a system is where ALL shaded regions overlap</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is usually the darkest shaded area on the graph</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Test a point in the overlap to verify it satisfies all inequalities</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Circle/ellipse shading is opposite of parabola/line shading</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Lines/parabolas: > means shade above</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Circles/ellipses: > means shade outside</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This catches many students—don''t mix them up!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>FLIP the inequality sign when multiplying or dividing BOTH SIDES by a negative number—this is the #1 mistake students make
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Number lines: use open circles for > and <, solid circles for ≥ and ≤; shade right for greater than, left for less than
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Linear/parabola inequalities: > and ≥ shade above the line, < and ≤ shade below; use dashed for strict (<, >), solid for inclusive (≤, ≥)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Circle/ellipse inequalities shade OPPOSITE: > and ≥ shade OUTSIDE, < and ≤ shade INSIDE
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('substitution', 'math', 'Topic 1.2 - Number Substitution Technique', 'Topic 1.2 - Number Substitution Technique...', 'intermediate', 30, 12, '<!--
LESSON TEMPLATE v5.0 (Math-Specific)
Subject: Math
Topic Number: 1.2
Topic: Number Substitution Technique
Lesson Key: substitution
-->

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 1: OPENING (2 SENTENCES MAX)
     CRITICAL: Must have:
     - MAXIMUM 2 sentences
     - ACT context (# of questions or %)
     - NO blue underlined terms here
     ======================================== -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Number substitution is a powerful test-taking strategy that transforms variable-heavy questions into simple arithmetic by plugging in concrete numbers. This technique works on 10-15% of ACT Math questions and is especially useful when you see multiple variables with few or no actual numbers!
</p>

<!-- ========================================
     SECTION 2: CONTENT (FLEXIBLE H3 SECTIONS)
     Each H3 = Major Concept
     Use BULLET POINTS with indents, NOT paragraphs
     ======================================== -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. What Is Number Substitution?
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Number substitution</strong> means replacing variables with simple numbers to solve problems using arithmetic instead of complex algebra
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Do you prefer working with numbers or variables? Most students prefer numbers!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Instead of manipulating <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">algebraic expressions</strong>, you work with concrete values</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Transform intimidating variable problems into straightforward arithmetic</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Why this strategy is so powerful:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Questions with many unknown <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">variables</strong> and few numbers often intimidate students</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Working with real numbers is faster and less error-prone than abstract algebra</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You can verify your answer immediately by checking it against the original problem</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Works even if you struggle with complex algebraic manipulation</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. The 4-Step Substitution Process
</h3>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Step 1: Pick Numbers for Variables
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Choose simple, easy-to-work-with numbers
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Avoid 0 and 1</strong> — these can lead to incorrect answers that seem to work</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Use 2, 3, 4, or 5</strong> — small numbers that are easy to calculate with</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Special cases:</strong> Use 10 for percent problems, 10 or 20 for group size problems</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Select different numbers for each variable
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If a question has x and y, pick x = 2 and y = 3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Using different values prevents confusion and ensures accurate results</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Follow any rules stated in the question
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If x must be negative and even, pick x = -2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If y must be greater than x, make sure your chosen values satisfy this</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Pay attention to constraints like "positive integers" or "odd numbers"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Step 2: Write Down Your Numbers
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Record your chosen values clearly
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Write them in your test booklet or scratch paper</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This prevents mistakes when plugging into <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">answer choices</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You''ll need to reference these values multiple times</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Step 3: Solve Using Your Numbers
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Work through the question using your chosen values
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Replace all variables with the numbers you picked</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Calculate step-by-step using basic arithmetic</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Find your numerical answer to the question</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h4 style="margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 0.3rem; font-weight: 600;">
Step 4: Test Answer Choices
</h4>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Plug your numbers into each answer choice
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The correct answer will match the numerical answer you found in Step 3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Only ONE answer choice will produce your target number</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Once you find the match, you''re done — bubble it in and move on!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 1 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->
<!-- Database: position=1, lesson_id=[UUID], shown AFTER teaching the process -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. When to Use Number Substitution
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Question asks "which of the following" or "in terms of..."
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Looking for an expression in terms of variables (m, n, x, y, etc.)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The question describes a situation with variables, not specific numbers</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Answer choices</strong> contain variables or expressions
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">✓ Choices like "0.7nm", "2x + 3", "5(x + 3)"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">✗ NOT for choices that are just numbers like 2, 5, 7, 10</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Question has multiple variables with no concrete numbers
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Problems like "n boxes with m items each"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Scenarios involving undefined quantities</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The algebra looks messy or time-consuming
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Setting up equations with variables would take too long</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Substitution often provides a faster path to the answer</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<!-- Example 2 will be inserted here by ExampleCard component -->
<!-- Database: position=2, lesson_id=[UUID] -->

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Common Question Types for Substitution
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Percent problems</strong> with variables
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Finding percentages of unknown quantities</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use 10 or 100 as your starting number for easy percent calculations</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "70% of n items" → pick n = 10, so 70% of 10 = 7</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Geometry transformation</strong> problems
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When shapes are scaled or modified</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: "length is tripled, width is halved"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Pick simple dimensions like length = 3, width = 2</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Trigonometry</strong> with unknown angles
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Questions like "if cos(2x) = a, which must be true?"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Pick a simple angle value (like x = 10° or x = 30°)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use calculator to find what a equals, then test answer choices</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Number property questions
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">"If x is odd and y is even, which must be odd?"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Pick specific values: x = 3 (odd), y = 4 (even)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Test each answer choice with your values</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

